1
00:00:46,826 --> 00:00:48,135
Chapter one.

2
00:00:48,202 --> 00:00:51,618
Sometimes, despite your
best efforts otherwise,

3
00:00:51,690 --> 00:00:53,698
life will give you lemons.

4
00:00:59,659 --> 00:01:02,790
When that happens,
you've got two choices,
friend.

5
00:01:03,371 --> 00:01:07,943
You can wear a sour face
or make lemonade.

6
00:02:55,952 --> 00:02:58,287
I never should have
booked this city.

7
00:02:58,352 --> 00:03:00,773
Come on,
come on, come on.

8
00:03:01,424 --> 00:03:02,668
Finally!

9
00:03:03,024 --> 00:03:04,039
Huh?

10
00:03:04,112 --> 00:03:06,087
What, did you swim here?
Might as well have.

11
00:03:06,161 --> 00:03:07,143
This is exactly
why I tell you

12
00:03:07,217 --> 00:03:08,297
you gotta fly in
the night before.

13
00:03:08,368 --> 00:03:09,546
The less time I spend
in this city, the better.

14
00:03:09,616 --> 00:03:11,504
I know, I know, I know.
But you'll be enthused
to know

15
00:03:11,569 --> 00:03:12,813
that I reamed
customer service.

16
00:03:12,881 --> 00:03:14,572
Your bag is gonna be
on the very next flight.

17
00:03:14,641 --> 00:03:15,786
But have no fear.

18
00:03:15,857 --> 00:03:19,152
There is a brand-new suit
waiting for you right here.

19
00:03:19,217 --> 00:03:20,329
Where'd you conjure
this up from?

20
00:03:20,401 --> 00:03:21,994
Well, rainmakers
make rain...

21
00:03:22,065 --> 00:03:23,374
Room key.
Voilà.

22
00:03:23,441 --> 00:03:25,580
There's a gorgeous
latte-colored
silk tie in there.

23
00:03:25,649 --> 00:03:27,624
I think you're gonna
love it. It's subtle...
Latte?

24
00:03:27,697 --> 00:03:29,486
Okay, there's a red
one in there, too. Okay?

25
00:03:29,554 --> 00:03:31,823
Can you please
just look your best?
Please, okay?

26
00:03:31,889 --> 00:03:36,046
Listen, all three
Unicom suits will fly
in from New York

27
00:03:36,114 --> 00:03:38,602
day after tomorrow
to see if we can
make a deal.

28
00:03:38,674 --> 00:03:40,200
All three of them?

29
00:03:40,274 --> 00:03:42,958
I'm Lane goddamned Marshall.

30
00:03:46,642 --> 00:03:49,195
Burke, for once
in your life, can you
please take the elevator?

31
00:03:49,267 --> 00:03:50,511
See you.

32
00:03:53,107 --> 00:03:55,179
Coming to the seminar?
Okay.

33
00:03:55,987 --> 00:03:57,874
Okay. Big day. Big day.

34
00:04:38,964 --> 00:04:40,459
And don't forget
the DVDs and audio books

35
00:04:40,533 --> 00:04:43,183
available for purchase
all through the week

36
00:04:43,252 --> 00:04:45,522
at our booth down the hall.

37
00:04:45,589 --> 00:04:48,655
And now,
without further ado,

38
00:04:48,725 --> 00:04:53,330
the author of the bestseller
A Path Through Grief,
my friend...

39
00:04:53,397 --> 00:04:56,561
No, my inspiration,
Burke Ryan.

40
00:05:18,454 --> 00:05:19,828
All right!

41
00:05:22,326 --> 00:05:24,269
Thanks, Lane. Wow!

42
00:05:25,174 --> 00:05:26,123
Whoo!

43
00:05:27,287 --> 00:05:29,523
You guys make
a guy feel good.

44
00:05:30,134 --> 00:05:32,207
I'm feeling okay.
How are you?

45
00:05:32,279 --> 00:05:33,872
A-Okay!

46
00:05:33,943 --> 00:05:37,140
Good.
Let me ask you a question.

47
00:05:37,207 --> 00:05:38,734
Any football fans
in the house?

48
00:05:40,375 --> 00:05:44,336
Certain college team
not too long ago
lost their season opener.

49
00:05:45,143 --> 00:05:47,445
They're going nowhere fast.

50
00:05:47,511 --> 00:05:50,992
Then something happened.
Thank you.

51
00:05:51,063 --> 00:05:54,893
An event that
changed everything
for their coach.

52
00:05:54,968 --> 00:05:57,008
The guy started
sleeping at the office,

53
00:05:57,144 --> 00:05:59,217
reinvented the playbook,
studied film.

54
00:05:59,288 --> 00:06:02,037
He was on the case 24-7.

55
00:06:02,168 --> 00:06:05,135
They went on to win
the national championship.

56
00:06:06,840 --> 00:06:10,899
Well, after all
the fanfare and the champagne,
he traipsed on home,

57
00:06:11,832 --> 00:06:16,143
went upstairs,
went to his closet

58
00:06:16,793 --> 00:06:20,306
and removed his Browning
double-barreled shotgun,

59
00:06:21,945 --> 00:06:25,393
put it to his chin
and pulled the trigger.

60
00:06:27,801 --> 00:06:30,485
See, the event
that changed it all

61
00:06:30,554 --> 00:06:32,626
back at the beginning
of the season?

62
00:06:32,826 --> 00:06:36,982
His brother,
his best friend in the world,
died of a heart attack.

63
00:06:39,066 --> 00:06:42,611
You might be able
to get back on the horse,
do great things.

64
00:06:42,682 --> 00:06:45,912
Hell, you might even win
a national championship.

65
00:06:45,978 --> 00:06:49,622
But if you don't
pay the piper,
he will come calling.

66
00:06:51,866 --> 00:06:55,828
I want to thank each
and every one of you

67
00:06:55,898 --> 00:07:00,209
for having the courage
to really feel
the loss of loved ones.

68
00:07:01,467 --> 00:07:03,289
I know it's not easy.

69
00:07:04,571 --> 00:07:06,229
I've been there.

70
00:07:07,419 --> 00:07:09,524
How are you?
You okay?

71
00:07:09,595 --> 00:07:10,806
A-Okay!

72
00:07:10,876 --> 00:07:13,112
Good. All right.
Say it one more time.
How are you?

73
00:07:13,179 --> 00:07:14,903
A-Okay!

74
00:07:14,971 --> 00:07:17,459
All right.
I'll see you in workshop.

75
00:07:26,620 --> 00:07:28,278
Perfect. Perfect.

76
00:07:29,308 --> 00:07:31,992
Good. Good. Great.

77
00:07:32,796 --> 00:07:34,706
Come on,
loosen up a little bit.
You need a drink?

78
00:07:34,780 --> 00:07:35,925
Maybe you need a drink.
Waiter!

79
00:07:35,996 --> 00:07:38,811
Please, no drink.
Chapter 12.

80
00:07:38,876 --> 00:07:41,942
"Alcohol's no more
a cure-all than a Band-Aid
on a bullet wound."

81
00:07:42,012 --> 00:07:44,914
All right. Now flash me
that sign of yours.

82
00:07:48,220 --> 00:07:50,043
Great. Give me that.

83
00:07:52,060 --> 00:07:55,443
Great. So, tell me,
what motivated the book?

84
00:07:56,445 --> 00:07:58,649
Uh, my wife died.

85
00:08:00,733 --> 00:08:01,944
I know.

86
00:08:02,749 --> 00:08:04,276
Why tell the whole world
about it?

87
00:08:09,022 --> 00:08:11,029
It was a way to coach myself
how to get through it.

88
00:08:11,102 --> 00:08:13,077
You know, I never
intended for anyone
to actually read it,

89
00:08:13,150 --> 00:08:17,143
but my manager
gave it to a publisher
and here I am.

90
00:08:17,214 --> 00:08:19,767
Yes, you are.
What happened?

91
00:08:20,318 --> 00:08:21,627
Uh...

92
00:08:25,918 --> 00:08:28,089
She was driving us
to dinner.

93
00:08:28,639 --> 00:08:30,843
Dog in the middle
of the road.

94
00:08:31,743 --> 00:08:33,466
Car swerved into a pole.

95
00:08:36,511 --> 00:08:38,235
She died instantly.

96
00:08:44,991 --> 00:08:47,031
It must have been awful.
I'm sorry.

97
00:08:47,999 --> 00:08:49,941
Appreciate it.

98
00:08:51,776 --> 00:08:53,816
Well, I think
I got what I needed.

99
00:08:53,888 --> 00:08:56,092
Great! Fantastic.
Nice to meet you,
Jessica.

100
00:08:56,160 --> 00:08:57,818
Nice to meet you.

101
00:08:58,368 --> 00:08:59,415
You take care.

102
00:08:59,488 --> 00:09:00,436
Thanks.

103
00:09:02,112 --> 00:09:04,283
This way, guys.
Follow Burke.

104
00:09:04,352 --> 00:09:06,141
All right, everybody.

105
00:09:06,208 --> 00:09:07,834
Those of you
who signed up for the
morning work group,

106
00:09:07,904 --> 00:09:09,278
you're in for a treat.

107
00:09:09,344 --> 00:09:10,326
Let's go! Let's go!

108
00:09:10,400 --> 00:09:12,310
Come out in the middle here.
Excuse us.

109
00:09:13,056 --> 00:09:15,576
Thank you.
Excuse us for a second.

110
00:09:15,648 --> 00:09:17,787
Sorry. Come on out here.

111
00:09:18,945 --> 00:09:20,832
Come on, everybody out.

112
00:09:21,473 --> 00:09:24,124
I want you to take
a moment and look around

113
00:09:24,193 --> 00:09:26,779
and tell me what you see
and what you hear.

114
00:09:26,850 --> 00:09:28,792
Okay? All right.

115
00:09:29,313 --> 00:09:30,393
Okay.

116
00:09:30,465 --> 00:09:31,447
Lorraine.

117
00:09:31,521 --> 00:09:33,212
Cars. Honking cars.

118
00:09:33,281 --> 00:09:34,743
Good. Natalie?

119
00:09:35,201 --> 00:09:36,249
Jackhammers.

120
00:09:36,321 --> 00:09:37,565
-Anybody else?
-Stoplights.

121
00:09:37,633 --> 00:09:38,811
Stoplights.
Cement.

122
00:09:38,881 --> 00:09:39,896
A homeless person.

123
00:09:39,970 --> 00:09:40,918
Trash.

124
00:09:40,994 --> 00:09:41,976
Middle fingers.

125
00:09:42,050 --> 00:09:43,163
Good. Excellent.

126
00:09:43,234 --> 00:09:46,463
Now remember that
and follow me.

127
00:09:47,586 --> 00:09:50,336
All right. Now what
do you see? Lorraine?

128
00:09:51,330 --> 00:09:52,705
The ocean.

129
00:09:53,602 --> 00:09:55,096
-Good.
-Trees.

130
00:09:55,906 --> 00:09:56,854
The Space Needle.

131
00:09:56,930 --> 00:09:58,108
Skyscrapers.

132
00:09:58,498 --> 00:09:59,993
Mount Rainier.

133
00:10:00,066 --> 00:10:01,495
Rivers.

134
00:10:01,570 --> 00:10:02,977
Beautiful rivers.

135
00:10:03,042 --> 00:10:04,417
The sun.
Good.

136
00:10:04,483 --> 00:10:05,825
Naked hot-tubber.

137
00:10:09,763 --> 00:10:12,927
Wow. Little bit different
up here, isn't it?

138
00:10:12,995 --> 00:10:15,548
And yet, it's the same.

139
00:10:16,675 --> 00:10:18,682
We haven't gone anywhere.

140
00:10:19,652 --> 00:10:22,881
We're just
looking at things from
a new perspective.

141
00:10:24,259 --> 00:10:29,759
Inside of each of you,
there are sirens,
honking horns and gridlock,

142
00:10:32,164 --> 00:10:36,059
but there's also this.

143
00:10:37,572 --> 00:10:39,678
We just have to do the work

144
00:10:40,709 --> 00:10:43,043
and climb the stairs
to find it.

145
00:10:44,324 --> 00:10:46,845
You have the reporter
at noon and I think
you're gonna like her a lot.

146
00:10:46,917 --> 00:10:48,324
Look, I don't
really give a rat's ass

147
00:10:48,389 --> 00:10:49,731
what your
cancellation policy is.

148
00:10:49,797 --> 00:10:51,226
I am leaving and
I want my money back.

149
00:10:51,301 --> 00:10:52,762
Sir, it's not that simple.
I'll be right back.

150
00:10:52,837 --> 00:10:54,364
Our cancellation
policy clearly...

151
00:10:54,437 --> 00:10:56,128
Hi. Becky?
What seems to be
the trouble here?

152
00:10:56,197 --> 00:10:59,044
Mr. Ryan, this gentleman
is refusing to adhere...

153
00:10:59,110 --> 00:11:01,149
Thank you.
Hi. I'm Burke.

154
00:11:01,894 --> 00:11:02,908
You are?

155
00:11:02,981 --> 00:11:04,061
Walter Mayfield.

156
00:11:04,133 --> 00:11:05,082
Walter. Where you from?

157
00:11:05,157 --> 00:11:06,881
Billings. Drove out
from Billings.

158
00:11:06,949 --> 00:11:08,542
Montana.
That's quite a drive.

159
00:11:08,614 --> 00:11:11,963
Yeah. Look, I don't think
this thing is for me, okay?

160
00:11:12,038 --> 00:11:13,893
Okay. You mind
if I ask why?

161
00:11:13,958 --> 00:11:17,984
Well, frankly,
my sister talked me
into it, and the...

162
00:11:18,054 --> 00:11:20,510
You know the whole...
And the feelings...

163
00:11:20,582 --> 00:11:22,339
I understand.
I understand.

164
00:11:22,407 --> 00:11:24,479
Can I ask you,
why did your sister think

165
00:11:24,550 --> 00:11:26,917
it was so important
for you to come here?

166
00:11:29,671 --> 00:11:30,816
My son.

167
00:11:30,887 --> 00:11:32,742
And what's his name?
Stephen.

168
00:11:32,807 --> 00:11:34,782
And when did he...
Does it really matter?

169
00:11:34,855 --> 00:11:37,473
It matters to me, Walter.
I'd like to hear.

170
00:11:42,631 --> 00:11:44,518
Do you have a picture?

171
00:12:02,120 --> 00:12:03,462
I'm sorry.

172
00:12:06,440 --> 00:12:08,131
Walter, I know
how you feel.
I've been there.

173
00:12:09,480 --> 00:12:12,033
My wife died.
Three years ago.

174
00:12:13,993 --> 00:12:15,422
I want you to know
that you've taken
the first step

175
00:12:15,497 --> 00:12:18,312
just by walking
through these doors,
and something inside you,

176
00:12:18,377 --> 00:12:21,857
whether you know it or not,
made you drive all this way.

177
00:12:23,849 --> 00:12:26,883
If you want to leave,
we'll honor your request.

178
00:12:27,849 --> 00:12:29,540
I hope you don't.

179
00:12:32,905 --> 00:12:35,491
Thanks, Becky.
Think about it.

180
00:12:42,953 --> 00:12:45,823
Chapter two.
Happiness is a state of mind

181
00:12:46,986 --> 00:12:49,507
and, like all things,
it takes practice.

182
00:12:49,578 --> 00:12:53,637
Devote five minutes a day
to smiling, just smiling,

183
00:12:55,594 --> 00:12:58,409
and after a while
it'll come naturally.

184
00:13:18,987 --> 00:13:21,321
Sorry. I didn't mean to...

185
00:13:35,948 --> 00:13:37,956
Hey, you forgot your pen!

186
00:13:51,565 --> 00:13:53,321
Quidnunc? Quidnunc?

187
00:14:06,349 --> 00:14:07,364
What can I get you?

188
00:14:07,437 --> 00:14:11,747
I would like another
Seven-and-Seven,
and a tomato juice

189
00:14:11,822 --> 00:14:12,770
for my virtuous friend here.

190
00:14:12,845 --> 00:14:13,925
Tomato juice.

191
00:14:13,998 --> 00:14:15,559
Thank you.

192
00:14:15,629 --> 00:14:18,412
So, as far as
Unicom knows,

193
00:14:18,478 --> 00:14:21,740
I'm a hair away
from signing a deal
with Time Warner. Okay?

194
00:14:21,806 --> 00:14:23,781
I'm expecting the offer
by lunchtime tomorrow.

195
00:14:23,855 --> 00:14:29,037
That means TV,
radio, publishing.
All of it.

196
00:14:29,998 --> 00:14:32,846
Are you as hot for me
right now as I am hot
for me right now?

197
00:14:32,910 --> 00:14:33,892
So hot.

198
00:14:33,966 --> 00:14:35,111
And check it.

199
00:14:35,407 --> 00:14:39,051
Ted Vernon, the CEO himself,
is gonna fly in
for the end of the seminar.

200
00:14:39,118 --> 00:14:42,152
My guess,
a little warm and fuzzy
contract-inking party.

201
00:14:42,223 --> 00:14:43,565
Who knows?

202
00:14:43,631 --> 00:14:45,038
Your drinks, gentlemen.

203
00:14:45,584 --> 00:14:46,696
Thank you.

204
00:14:50,639 --> 00:14:52,068
It's a long way
from booking you gigs

205
00:14:52,144 --> 00:14:54,565
writing columns
for Psychology Today, huh?

206
00:15:01,008 --> 00:15:02,950
I'll get you a Learjet.

207
00:15:03,696 --> 00:15:04,678
You like Learjets?

208
00:15:04,752 --> 00:15:05,930
Lane.

209
00:15:06,672 --> 00:15:09,323
Come on. You know
that's not why I wrote it.

210
00:15:11,088 --> 00:15:14,405
You do know that
you're helping people,
right, man?

211
00:15:18,384 --> 00:15:20,173
This is your moment.

212
00:15:20,912 --> 00:15:23,815
You have to give
yourself permission
to enjoy it, brother.

213
00:15:24,561 --> 00:15:27,016
Come on, man.
Live a little.

214
00:15:27,825 --> 00:15:28,808
Yeah.

215
00:15:28,881 --> 00:15:29,863
Yeah.

216
00:15:36,241 --> 00:15:37,354
What?

217
00:15:54,130 --> 00:15:55,624
You're right.

218
00:16:09,555 --> 00:16:11,344
Excuse me. I'm sorry.

219
00:16:11,923 --> 00:16:15,469
Hi. Do you remember me?
From the hallway upstairs?

220
00:16:15,539 --> 00:16:17,361
You dropped your pen.

221
00:16:19,123 --> 00:16:20,203
Um...

222
00:16:20,595 --> 00:16:23,246
Would you like to
have a cup of coffee?

223
00:16:28,180 --> 00:16:29,128
Ah.

224
00:16:29,523 --> 00:16:30,734
Right. Um...

225
00:16:32,020 --> 00:16:35,249
Well, we could bring
him along if you want.
Double your pleasure.

226
00:16:42,228 --> 00:16:44,912
I'm sorry.
I... I... You...

227
00:16:50,133 --> 00:16:51,278
See you, Ricky.

228
00:16:51,349 --> 00:16:52,429
Later, Eloise.

229
00:17:13,014 --> 00:17:15,697
Hey, baby. What's this?
Delivery.

230
00:17:15,990 --> 00:17:17,299
Wow.
I was in the
neighborhood,

231
00:17:17,366 --> 00:17:18,675
so I figured
I'd bring you lunch

232
00:17:18,741 --> 00:17:20,684
'cause I knew you'd
be working so hard.

233
00:17:20,757 --> 00:17:21,706
Wow, you didn't
have to do that.

234
00:17:21,782 --> 00:17:23,124
Polished up,
ready to go.

235
00:17:23,190 --> 00:17:24,172
Hey, Eloise.

236
00:17:24,246 --> 00:17:25,293
Hi, Ian.

237
00:17:25,814 --> 00:17:27,472
How's your boss
treating you today?

238
00:17:27,542 --> 00:17:29,168
Oh, he's all right.

239
00:17:29,239 --> 00:17:32,337
The lead singer
of the Stereo Kings
trashed his Les Paul.

240
00:17:32,407 --> 00:17:35,407
Look at that
fretboard, man.
As good as new.

241
00:17:35,478 --> 00:17:36,624
Make sure
he signs for it.

242
00:17:36,695 --> 00:17:37,971
No problem.

243
00:17:39,127 --> 00:17:40,305
Did you have company?

244
00:17:41,878 --> 00:17:42,827
Um...

245
00:17:42,935 --> 00:17:46,284
Yeah. I told you
Frank and I were
working last night.

246
00:17:47,255 --> 00:17:48,815
Frank wears lipstick?

247
00:17:50,616 --> 00:17:52,307
Hey, listen.
EI, it's not
what you think.

248
00:17:52,376 --> 00:17:53,652
It's business.
Totally platonic.

249
00:17:53,719 --> 00:17:55,246
You know what?
You used
that one last time.

250
00:17:55,319 --> 00:17:57,905
No, she's got ties
to Sony. Hey!

251
00:17:57,976 --> 00:18:00,397
Listen to me.
You gotta listen
to me. Eloise!

252
00:18:00,472 --> 00:18:02,228
I don't want to hear it.

253
00:19:14,907 --> 00:19:16,084
How you
